"Monserud R.A., Yang Y., Huang S., Tchebakova N.","Potential change in lodgepole pine site index and distribution under climatic change in Alberta",2008,"Canadian Journal of Forest Research","38","2",,"343","352",,,10.1139/X07-166,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-40749092491&partnerID=40&md5=974d9dd30f4dcba27f8dc6bd0d7cd45c","PNW Research Station, USDA Forest Service, 620 SW Main Street, Portland, OR 97205, United States; Forest Management Branch, Public Lands and Forests Division, AB Sustainable Resource Development, 9920-108 Street, Edmonton, AB T5K 2M4, Canada; Sukachev Forest Institute, Russian Academy of Sciences (Siberian Branch), 660036 Krasnoyarsk, Russian Federation","Monserud, R.A., PNW Research Station, USDA Forest Service, 620 SW Main Street, Portland, OR 97205, United States; Yang, Y., Forest Management Branch, Public Lands and Forests Division, AB Sustainable Resource Development, 9920-108 Street, Edmonton, AB T5K 2M4, Canada; Huang, S., Forest Management Branch, Public Lands and Forests Division, AB Sustainable Resource Development, 9920-108 Street, Edmonton, AB T5K 2M4, Canada; Tchebakova, N., Sukachev Forest Institute, Russian Academy of Sciences (Siberian Branch), 660036 Krasnoyarsk, Russian Federation","We estimated the impact of global climate change on lodgepole pine (Pinus contorta Dougl. ex Loud. var. latifolia Engelm.) site productivity in Alberta based on the Alberta Climate Model and the A2 SRES climate change scenario projections from three global circulation models (CGCM2, HADCM3, and ECHAM4). Considerable warming is apparent in all three models. On average, the increases in mean GDD5 (growing degree-days &gt;5 °C) are 18%, 38%, and 65% by the 2020s, 2050s, and 2080s, respectively. Change in precipitation is essentially nil. This results in proportional increases in dryness index. We used the dryness index to predict the potential future range and GDD5 to predict its potential productivity. Generally, lodgepole pine site index is predicted to increase steadily by 3 m for each 30-year period. Offsetting this increase is a large reduction in suitable area as drying increases. At first, the warming increases the potential range up to 67% by the 2020s but then shrinks from 34% to 58% of its current area by 2080. Such major changes will need to be considered when setting long-term forest management plans. The increased risk of both wildfire and insect outbreaks further compounds this planning problem, especially because these disturbance events can interact and further increase risk. © 2008 NRC.",,"Climate change; Problem solving; Risk analysis; Global circulation models; Potential productivity; Forestry; circulation modeling; climate change; climate effect; coniferous tree; estimation method; forest management; global climate; risk assessment; spatial distribution; warming; wildfire; Forestry; Problem Solving; Risk Assessment; Seasonal Variation; Alberta; Canada; North America; Hexapoda; Pinus contorta",,,,,,"Alberta Environment. 2005. Alberta Climate Model (ACM) to provide climate estimates (1961-1990) for any location in Alberta from its geographic coordinates. Publ. T/749. Alberta Environment, Edmonton, AltaAssmann, E., (1970) The principles of forest yield studies, , Pergamon Press, Oxford, U.K; Barrow, E., Yu, G., (2005) Climate scenarios for Alberta, , www.parc.ca/research_pub_scenarios.htm, Prairie Adaptation Research Collaborative, Regina, Sask; Box, E.O., Crumpacker, D.W., Hardin, P.S., Predicted effects of climatic change on distribution of ecologically important native tree and shrub species in Florida (1999) Clim. Change, 41, pp. 213-248. , doi:10.1023/A: 1005483507351; Flannigan, M.D., Logan, K.A., Amiro, B.D., Skinner, W.R., Stocks, B.J., Future area burned in Canada (2005) Clim. Change, 72, pp. 1-16. , doi:10.1007/s10584-005-5935-y; Flato, G.M., Boer, G.J., Lee, W.G., McFarlane, N.A., Ramsden, D., Reader, M.C., Weaver, A.J., The Canadian centre for climate modelling and